# ─── Database ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Neon Postgres → console.neon.tech → your project → Connect.
# You need BOTH strings. They differ only by "-pooler" in the hostname.
#
# ⚠ Use the DIRECT connection — the hostname must NOT contain "-pooler".
#
# We measured both against the same database:
#     through Neon's PgBouncer pooler   382 ms per query
#     direct                             72 ms per query
#
# Five times slower. `pgbouncer=true` forces Prisma to disable prepared
# statements, so every query is re-parsed, and the pooler adds a hop of its own.
# A page firing ~15 queries was paying ~1.5 s of pure overhead — every click took
# 2 seconds.
#
# The pooler exists to stop serverless functions exhausting Postgres connections
# under real traffic. At this scale that problem does not exist. If this app ever
# took real load, the answer would be to reintroduce the pooler AND cache — not to
# pay 300 ms on every query today for a problem we don't have.
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://user:password@ep-xxxx.ap-southeast-1.aws.neon.tech/neondb?sslmode=require&connection_limit=10&connect_timeout=15"

# Same endpoint — used by `prisma db push` and migrations, which take Postgres
# advisory locks that a pooler will not pass through.
DIRECT_URL="postgresql://user:password@ep-xxxx.ap-southeast-1.aws.neon.tech/neondb?sslmode=require"

# ─── Auth ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Signing key for the session JWT. Generate one with:
#   node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(32).toString('hex'))"
SESSION_SECRET="change-me-to-a-32-byte-random-hex-string"

# ─── Seed ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Password given to every seeded demo account (admin@assetflow.io, etc.)
SEED_PASSWORD="assetflow123"
